1
00:00:05,669 --> 00:00:07,608
In the words of Emerson,
he said,

2
00:00:07,608 --> 00:00:09,958
“Imitation is suicide!”

3
00:00:10,204 --> 00:00:12,281
[Imitation is Suicide]

4
00:00:12,281 --> 00:00:15,283
That’s how he put it, 
“imitation is suicide.”

5
00:00:15,283 --> 00:00:16,866
What does it mean?

6
00:00:16,866 --> 00:00:17,780
How can he say that?

7
00:00:17,780 --> 00:00:20,655
Because if you’re imitating
something else,

8
00:00:20,655 --> 00:00:23,198
if you’re imitating
someone else,

9
00:00:23,198 --> 00:00:27,130
you’re not being yourself—
you’re killing yourself.

10
00:00:27,806 --> 00:00:31,054
That’s the implication.

11
00:00:31,054 --> 00:00:38,287
By imitation you become … 
it’s not you! It’s not real!

12
00:00:40,134 --> 00:00:46,345
Sometimes I’ve mentioned acting,

13
00:00:46,345 --> 00:00:51,593
and the famous Russian
acting teacher Stanislavski.

14
00:00:51,594 --> 00:00:55,448
What later became known
as the Method.

15
00:00:55,448 --> 00:00:59,115
Stanislavski, his system
—and this is for actors—he’s saying,

16
00:00:59,115 --> 00:01:08,310
“If you will imitate the behaviour
of the character that you’re portraying—

17
00:01:08,780 --> 00:01:12,716
you’ll dress like them; you’ll move
like them; you’ll talk like them;

18
00:01:12,716 --> 00:01:18,325
so many ways 
you’ll imitate them comprehensively—

19
00:01:18,325 --> 00:01:23,831
then the point will come where suddenly
you have an epiphany

20
00:01:23,831 --> 00:01:27,592
and you’ve become 
that character.

21
00:01:27,592 --> 00:01:30,383
That’s his way of teaching,

22
00:01:30,383 --> 00:01:34,405
and it later became known
in America as “The Method”.

23
00:01:34,405 --> 00:01:39,041
It’s a particular method
employed by actors,

24
00:01:39,041 --> 00:01:42,025
so they just named it “The Method”.
Method acting.

25
00:01:42,025 --> 00:01:44,975
“Oh he’s the Method actor.”

26
00:01:44,975 --> 00:01:47,644
So they’ll imitate everything
about that character,

27
00:01:47,644 --> 00:01:51,565
and go so deeply in that character
they won’t come out.

28
00:01:51,565 --> 00:01:55,569
Even when the camera’s not rolling,
they’re still, quote, “in character”:

29
00:01:55,569 --> 00:01:58,583
speaking like that person;
moving like them;

30
00:01:58,583 --> 00:02:02,361
if they walk with a limp,
they’re limping; everything.

31
00:02:02,361 --> 00:02:06,528
Drives some people crazy,
but that’s what they do.

32
00:02:06,528 --> 00:02:08,333
That’s for actors.

33
00:02:08,333 --> 00:02:12,750
The method of
prākṛta sahajiyās is similar:

34
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:15,845
you see, imitate, 
exalted devotees;

35
00:02:15,845 --> 00:02:19,698
dress like them; talk like them;
walk like them; try to think like them;

36
00:02:19,698 --> 00:02:25,684
mimic their behavior, and you’ll find
at a certain point you’ll become them.

37
00:02:25,684 --> 00:02:30,114
But the fact of the matter is,
you’ve not become them—

38
00:02:30,114 --> 00:02:31,817
you’re acting.

